{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16096"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16096"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.26,0.52,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59636"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4134"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents for her first antenatal visit at 12 weeks gestation. An ultrasound reveals an abnormal placenta with multiple cystic spaces. Subsequent genetic testing shows triploidy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological features of a partial molar pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absence of fetal tissue and blood vessels","Diffuse trophoblastic hyperplasia with regular villous contours","Focal trophoblastic hyperplasia with irregular villous contours","Complete absence of trophoblastic hyperplasia","Normal villous architecture with increased vascularity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA partial molar pregnancy demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal trophoblastic hyperplasia with irregular villous contours\u003C/strong\u003E. These lesions typically contain both abnormal placental tissue and fetal tissue, with a triploid chromosomal complement (69 chromosomes).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence of fetal tissue and blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of complete moles, not partial moles which typically contain fetal tissue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse trophoblastic hyperplasia with regular villous contours\u003C/strong\u003E - Diffuse hyperplasia is seen in complete moles; partial moles show focal changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete absence of trophoblastic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - Partial moles do show trophoblastic hyperplasia, though focal rather than diffuse\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal villous architecture with increased vascularity\u003C/strong\u003E - Partial moles show abnormal villous architecture with irregular contours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of fetal tissue, nucleated red blood cells, and focal rather than diffuse trophoblastic changes helps distinguish partial from complete molar pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A partial molar pregnancy contains both abnormal placental tissue and fetal tissue, typically with triploid chromosomes (69 chromosomes).","Partial moles show focal trophoblastic hyperplasia and irregular villous contours on histological examination.","Fetal tissue and nucleated red blood cells are commonly present in partial moles, unlike complete moles."],"references":["Al Ghadeer HA, Al Kishi N, Algurini KH, Albesher AB, AlGhadeer MR, Alsalman AA, Bubshait AA, Alkishi BM. Partial Molar Pregnancy With Normal Karyotype. Cureus. 2022 Oct 31;14(10):e30934. doi: 10.7759/cureus.30934. PMID: 36465796; PMCID: PMC9711909.","Ghassemzadeh S, Farci F, Kang M. Hydatidiform Mole. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459155/","De Franciscis P, Schiattarella A, Labriola D, Tammaro C, Messalli EM, La Mantia E, Montella M, Torella M. A partial molar pregnancy associated with a fetus with intrauterine growth restriction delivered at 31 weeks: a case report. J Med Case Rep. 2019 Jul 4;13(1):204. doi: 10.1186/s13256-019-2150-4. PMID: 31269962; PMCID: PMC6610795.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59636"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16096"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59636"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:35:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:36:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags"